@node "intro" "Introduction - A humorous beginning!"

Introduction:

 This  manual  is meant to help you use TrapConfig.  It is also meant to be
more  than  a  BIT entertaining.  You see, we like what we do, playin' with
them  there  'Miga  compooters.   Can't get enough of them.  Kinda like the
puppies  we  never  had  as children, you know?  I mean I wanted one really
bad,  I  begged,  I  pleaded,  but all my parents did was give me a Siamese
Fighting  Fish, and named it "Rover".  It died the first time I took it for
a  walk, on a leash.  Sniff.  But Rover multitasked as well as a MacIntosh.
That's why I got an Amiga.

 Sorry.   I  digress.  But these being "Gonzo Docs" your humble author will
be  doing  that a lot.  So what.  This isn't Rocket Science.  It's Computer
Science.  Big diff.

So  We  hope these docs will be a help.  Some of them have been culled from
the  "Official"  TrapDoor docs, for reference, and have little "addendums",
with  tricks,  tips,  and  clarifications, sprung from years of beating our
heads  against the TrapDoor.  Keep in mind, this program is so easy to use,
to  generate  a TrapDoor.cfg file, you can train an ape to do it.  In fact,
one of our beta testers is a Cerebus Monkey, with a 4000/030.

Smart bastard. Wears diapers, but a smart bastard.

New TrapDoor/TrapConfig users: BOY! are you getting off easy!

***************************************************************************

Our story, thus far:


 It's  3:00  AM.   There's  a  light  on  in  a  window, in a usually quiet
residential  neighborhood.   It's  the  home  of  a  young man.  Let's call
him.....  Mendicant.

 Mendicant  is  known  by  his friends to be a computer afficianado, but in
that  world  of bleary-eyed, pasty-complected, auto-masochists, he is known
to be really, really bull goose loony.  Gone.  Toast.

Why, you might ask?

 The self-flagallating sumbitch owns one of those "Migos". Or whatnot.

 I  mean,  who runs one of those?  Certainly not too many of the "Big Guys"
who are involved in the latest thing Mendicant has discovered to suck money
out of his pitiful bank account, by Quantum-oriented orders of magnatude.

 Fidonet.   He  needs Fidonet.  He wants Fidonet.  Every fiber of his being
screams  "FIDONET!!".   He  knows  he  won't  be complete until he can call
Tierra-del-Fuego,  at  peak cost hour, (Due to his polling slot) to get the
"AMIGA" echo, whereupon he can get into arguments with people as to why the
Amiga  multitasks  FAR,  FAR  better  that  a Hal 9000, or a new Cray, with
16,000  DEC  Alpha  parrelel processors running at 100mhz, bubbles and all.
He  also  looks forward to his first feed cut from Joyce and Roy, a feat of
superhuman stupidity, and hubris in itself.

 But first he faces a daunting, and superhuman task.

 Setting up just one little program.  A program that comes with some of the
best docs ever written for any program, on any platform.  Docs distilled to
a  clarity  unriveled by the best Swedish Vodka.  No matter.  Mensa members
have  been  reduced  to  the level of Gibbering Striped-assed Mandrills, on
Ibogaine,  Curare,  and  Cane-Toad  Sweat,  by these docs.  Strong men have
disassembled.   Women fainted.  Children wept.  Dave Haynie got hysterical,
explosive   diaherria.    What   is   this  demonic  instrumentation,  this
Lovecraftian source of eldritch horror?

 TrapDoor.   It  starts  with  "T".   We  all know that stands for trouble.
Trouble in River City.

 Back  to  Mendicant:   as we look in the window, we see him looking into a
monitor.   Well, looking is just not descriptive enough, as ol'Mendy's eyes
are  bugging  out  on  12  inch stalks, and a fine patina of oily sweat has
formed   on  his  forehead,  upper-lip(under  his  requisite  thin,  cheesy
post-pubescent attempted Techno-stud moustache), and nether-regions.  He is
also enjoying bouts of nervous, uncontrolled flatulence.

 Why,  you might ask?  Well he has been working for 11 hours, trying to set
up  TrapDoor.   He  has  experienced  inumerable  failures to load the damn
thing.   He hasn't eaten for twelve hours, and had had 6 too many Big Reds.
He  has  tried  to find the rumored TrapDoor guru, Chris Kloiber, but Chris
has  walled himself up in a hermitage in a Tibetan Monistary.  Mendicant is
at  his  wits  end.   He leans over, places his acne-marked forehead on the
keyboard  (Depositing  a small amount of pus, thereon.  Blech.), and starts
to  quietly  weep.   He utters a small prayer to the gods of TrapDoor, Max,
Martin,  Rene, or Cthulhu.  No one is really sure who the correct one might
be.

 There  is  a  light  at  the window.  It is faint at first, but grows ever
brighter,  until it is a blinding red light, the same shage as the SD light
on a 16.8 Dual Standard, w/ Fax (Copyright who knows?  USRobotics.  For God
Sakes  don't even MENTION this to Stephen Hendricks, or Bob Germer!).  Soon
the  light  materializes  into  a  figure,  floating in the air.  Mendicant
cannot  make  out  the  details,  as  the  caffiene  in  the  Big  Reds has
semi-perminently destroyed the part of his brain that controls the movement
in  his eyes, leaving him with less ability to focus on a stationary object
than  a  Department  of Defense Testing Pig, on Nerve Gas, and a near-fatal
7.62mm  headwound.   Intuitively,  he  feels  it is either Tinkerbell, Asha
Develder,  or  Roger  Clark, dressed in the worst drag his caffiene, sugar,
and  Red Dye #21-crazed mind could ever imagine.  The etherial being smites
him smartly, around the head, and shoulders with something that is either a
Staff  (+10)  left over from a Hack & Slash session, or a wand, and belches
one word:

                                 "TrapConfig"

 And  the word is made flesh.  Or a cheap Midwest MicroExchange floppy left
sitting on his Hard Drive.

 And  it  was good.  But not as good as the stale Fritos he had next to his
frayed Cons, on the floor.  Mendicant ate, knowing deliverance was at hand.
@endnode

@node "pepsi" "System Requirements"
Requirements for TrapConfig V1.1:

  Workbench 2.0+

  libs:
     asl.library V36+
     intuition.library V37+
     graphics.library V37+
     gadtools.library V37+

  TrapDoor 1.83

All  the  required libs should be included with Workbench 2.0+.  The reason
for the Workbench 2.0 is because alot of the gadgets are 2.0 specific.

This is the final unregistered release.  If you are interested in
registering this lovely utility, please refer to the docs directory.  All
the information that you need is located in a file called
Register.TXT..Enjoy!!!

TrapConfig is (c) 1993 BitMap Productions.

@endnode

@node "percent" "Embeded Percent-Commands"
  4.1. Embedded Percent-Commands

       The  @{"AFTERSESSION" link aftersession},  @{"BBSCOMMAND" link bbscommand},  @{"DIALER" link dialer} and @{"FREQUEST" link frequest} keywords allow
     you  to  specify  a  commmand-string that will be executed.  In these
     command-strings,  the  following  embedded  %-commands are permitted.
     All of them are case-sensitive.

          %b ... baudrate (between computer and modem)
          %B ... baudrate (of the actual connection)
          %s ... serial device name
          %u ... serial device unit number
          %f ... serial device flags
          %r ... unique random number (timestamp)
          %l ... name of logfile
          %Z ... zone number of the other system
          %N ... net number of the other system
          %F ... fido node number of the other system
          %P ... point number of the other system
          %n ... complete FidoNet address of the other system
          %% ... %

       For  the  FREQUEST  keyword, the following sequences are allowed in
     addition to the above:

          %i ... name of the .REQ file (input file)
          %o ... name of the .RLO file (output file)
          %S ... name of Sysop of other system

@endnode

